en.label: Denomination of the issuing authority
en.description: As defined in the ORG Ontology, a preferred label is used to provide the primary, legally recognised name of the organisation. An organisation may only have one such name in any given language. Primary names may be provided in multiple languages with multiple instances of the preferred label property.
en.example: IRN -  Institute of Registry and Notary.

en.label: Issuing place
en.description: The Location where the Domicile Registration Evidence was issued.

en.label: Certifies domicile registration
en.description: Attesting in a formal way the domicile registration.

en.label: Inhabitant's details
en.description: Person living in the residence or domicile who requested the evidence

en.label: Address of the registered domicile
en.description: Current domicilie inhabitated by the person

en.label: Admin unit level 2
en.description: The region of the address, usually a county, state or other such area that typically encompasses several localities.

en.label: Admin unit level 1
en.description: The uppermost administrative unit for the address, almost always a country. Best practice is to use the ISO 3166-1 code.

en.label: PoBox
en.description: The Post Office Box number. INSPIRE's name for this is 'postalDeliveryIdentifier' for which it uses the locator designator property with a type attribute of that name. This vocabulary separates out the Post Office Box for greater independence of technology.

en.label: Thoroughface
en.description: Quoting from the INSPIRE guidelines, a thoroughfare is: 'an address component that represents the name of a passage or way through from one location to another. A thoroughfare is not necessarily a road, it might be a waterway or some other feature.

en.label: Locator designator
en.description: The locator designator is defined by the INSPIRE guidelines as 'a number or a sequence of characters that uniquely identifies the locator within the relevant scope(s). The full identification of the locator could include one or more locator designators.' In simpler terms, this is the building number, apartment number, etc. For an address such as 'Flat 3, 17 Bridge Street', the locator is 'flat 3, 17.'

en.label: Locator name
en.description: Based on the INSPIRE guidelines, locator name is defined as: 'Proper noun(s) applied to the real world entity identified by the locator. The locator name could be the name of the property or complex, of the building or part of the building, or it could be the name of a room inside a building. The key difference between a locator and a locator name is that the latter is a proper name and is unlikely to include digits. For example, 'Shumann, Berlaymont' is a meeting room within the European Commission headquarters for which locator name is more appropriate than locator.

en.label: Address area
en.description: Taking the definition from INSPIRE, the address area is: the name or names of a geographic area or locality that groups a number of addressable objects for addressing purposes, without being an administrative unit.' This would typically be part of a city, a neighbourhood or village.

en.label: Post name
en.description: The key postal division of the address, usually the city. (INSPIRE's definition is 'One or more names created and maintained for postal purposes to identify a subdivision of addresses and postal delivery points.)

en.label: Post code
en.description: The post code (a.k.a postal code, zip code etc.). Post codes are common elements in many countries' postal address systems.

en.label: Person
en.description: An individual natural person who may be dead or alive, but not imaginary.

en.label: Date of birth
en.description: The day on which the person was born.

en.label: Year
en.description: A gregorian calendar year. The value space of Year is the set of Gregorian calendar years as defined in § 5.2.1 of ISO 8601. Specifically, it is a set of one-year long, non-periodic instances e.g. lexical 1999 to represent the whole year 1999, independent of how many months and days this year has.

en.label: Month
en.description: A gregorian month that recurs every year. The value space of Month is the space of a set of calendar months as defined in § 3 of ISO 8601. Specifically, it is a set of one-month long, yearly periodic instances.

en.label: Day
en.description: A gregorian day that recurs, specifically a day of the month such as the 5th of the month. The value space of Day is the space of a set of calendar dates as defined in § 3 of ISO 8601. Specifically, it is a set of one-day long, monthly periodic instances.

en.label: Gender
en.description: The chromosomal state, and reproductive organs and structures of a Person that allows them to be distinguished as female or male or undetermined.

en.label: Place of birth
en.description: The Location where the person was born.

en.label: Person name
en.description: The family name and given name of a Person. At least one of the two must exist.

en.label: Family name
en.description: A family name is usually shared by members of a family. This attribute also carries prefixes or suffixes which are part of the family name, e.g. 'de Boer', 'van de Putte', 'von und zu Orlow'. Multiple family names, such as are commonly found in Hispanic countries, are recorded in the single family name field so that, for example, Miguel de Cervantes Saavedra's Family Name would be recorded as 'de Cervantes Saavedra'.

en.label: Given name
en.description: A given name, or multiple given names, are the denominator(s) that identify an individual within a family. These are given to a Person by his or her parents at birth or may be legally recognised as 'given names' through a formal process. All given names are ordered in one field so that, for example, the given name for Johann Sebastian Bach is 'Johann Sebastian'.

en.label: Person Identifier
en.description: The identifier relation is used to link a Person to any formally issued Identifier for that Person.

en.label: Citizenship
en.description: The citizenship relationship links a Person to a Jurisdiction that has conferred citizenship rights on the individual such as the right to vote, to receive certain protection from the community or the issuance of a passport.

en.label: Identifier
en.description: Many organisations are referred to by an acronym or some other identifier. For example, among the EU institutions, the ECB is the identifier for the European Central Bank, OLAF for the European AntiN/AFraud Office, and so on. These are formally recognised by the European Commission which provides a list of such acronyms. Analogous lists should be used in other contexts.

en.label: Denomination
en.description: As defined in the ORG Ontology, a preferred label is used to provide the primary, legally recognised name of the organisation. An organisation may only have one such name in any given language. Primary names may be provided in multiple languages with multiple instances of the preferred label property.
en.example: IRN -   Institute of Registry and Notary.

en.label: Scheme URI

en.description: The type of identifier issued (if the authority issues more than one type of identifier).

The gender of an individual should be recorded using a controlled vocabulary that is appropriate for the specific context. In some cases the chromosomal or physical state of an individual will be more important than the gender that they express, in others the reverse will be true. What is always important is that the controlled vocabulary used to describe an individual's gender is stated explicitly.
